        <body>
            <p>The authors present a convincing and well-designed framework that presents opportunities for further studies and practical application both from the perspective of both cultural policy and management. The paper engages convincingly with existing literature on the commons, and the interdisciplinary perspective adopted by the authors proves to be particularly effective for the purpose of their paper. This is a welcome and rigorous contribution to the study of the cultural commons.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The necessity of rethinking the management of GLAMS is well contextualized. However, considering that the paper focuses on memory institutions, it is necessary for the authors to discuss the notion &#x201c;contested heritage&#x201d; (Silverman, 2010). De-colonial, anti-racist and repatriation movements have significantly changed heritage discourse in Europe; furthermore, heritage has become an arena for the discussion of controversial historical figures, resulting with protests and, in some instances, the removal of statues or other heritage sites. This contextual element is important for the paper for two reasons: first, it is necessary to discuss how the governance mechanisms proposed by the authors can address these issues and possibly generate democratic pathways to the management of contested heritage. Secondly, the notion of contested heritage raises useful questions about the relationship between &#x201c;heritage&#x201d; and &#x201c;community&#x201d;: whose heritage? Whose memory? Whose values? Whose community? &#x00a0;The authors state: &#x201c;We believe that that new framework can offer a device to all those communities that are assembled through a collective interest over a particular historic past&#x201d;: are there any examples/explanations in the existing literature of how these communities are formed, and how they operate? The authors reference Bailey and Marcucci 2014 to illustrate this point, but the case discussed by Bailey and Marcucci is a very particular one, Teatro Valle: this theatre was occupied by activists and professionals of the cultural sector, who were evicted from the theatre in 2014, as the local council did not recognize nor the occupation nor the management of the theatre by the commoners as legitimate. This source illustrate how the sustainability of the commons is endangered by a lack of legal recognition of the commons and by the hostility of local authorities towards forms of collective management that operate autonomously and in opposition to existing policies. All these problems are useful in thinking about the potential of commons-oriented practices in the context of GLAMS in addressing issues of inequality in the context of GLAMS.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The issue of &#x201c;community&#x201d; could be further examined in the analysis of the existing literature on the cultural commons; in particular, I think that the work of Merima Bruncevic on law, arts and the commons could be an interesting source for the authors to examine.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> From a conceptual standpoint, more clarity is required in connection to the following questions:&#x00a0; 
                <list list-type="order">
                    <list-item>
                        <p>How flexible is the framework presented by the authors? In order to self-describe as a &#x201c;commons-oriented GLAM&#x201d;, does an organization need to satisfy all the criteria contained in the framework, or is this an adaptable model? More broadly, this question refers to the extent to which the framework is to be understood as normative for the sector.&#x00a0;</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>What are the challenges that the authors expect GLAMs to face when engaging with the framework in terms of scale, expertise and resources? Which GLAMs might find it easier to implement?</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>From a policy perspective, the legal recognition of the status of &#x201c;commons&#x201d; tends to vary significantly across Europe (and even across different cities in the same country, as it is the case in Italy). How does the existence, or the lack thereof, of policy on the commons affect the implementation of the framework proposed in this paper? Does the framework offer any opportunity to policymakers to engage with this issue?&#x00a0;</p>
                    </list-item>
                </list> That said, I congratulate the authors on their rigorous work; the model they propose is clear and well structured, and directly addresses some of the major challenges of the contemporary cultural sector.</p>
