            <p>The paper presents a cogent and comprehensive review of the relevant literature and presents an argument that contributes to debates in the field. &#x00a0;There is a great deal to praise in its structure, content and presentation. The authors clearly are scholars of the issues they are assessing.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> At the heart of this paper is the argument that so-called GLAMs can be conceptualized as a commons and that commons governance ideas may help the GLAMs adapt to contemporary demands on &#x201c;memory institutions&#x201d; to address local concerns.&#x00a0; I wholeheartedly agree that the GLAM sector globally is, and should be, undergoing a shift in focus from universal conceptions of cultural value to reflect both the contentious history underlying collections of items, whose origin stories are rooted in colonial or other exploitative endeavours in past centuries, and the distance of most GLAMs from the interests, needs and priorities of their adjacent communities.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> As the authors correctly note within the paper, I and others have in the past been skeptical of applying commons concepts to the heritage sector.&#x00a0; While I think the authors fairly present this critique, they are nonetheless confident in asserting that &#x201c;it is clear that GLAMS fall into the category of new commons&#x201d; (p 6).&#x00a0; This leads them to a conceptual framework that characterizes a commons-based GLAM as one that is or can be &#x201c;a commons&#x2019; resource, a self-governing community, and a set of self-legislated rules and norms&#x201d; (p6). This positioning reflects a tendency among scholars analysing heritage through a commons lens to simultaneously overemphasize the potential of GLAMs (and other heritage resources) to be governed as commons while, at the same moment, to underweight the governance considerations that make this highly unlikely to be true.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> At bottom, and I write here as a board member of museums and other cultural institutions as well as a scholar of Ostrom&#x2019;s work, this is the point on which I part company with the authors and hope they will address the issues I raise substantively in a revision.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> First, I believe they need to differentiate among types and scales of GLAM institutions. For example, I can readily accept their arguments if applied to community museums with low overheads and a mission focused on local community needs (such as one finds in many emerging countries in the Asia, Africa and Latin America).&#x00a0; These exist at small scale around the world and likely can (and should) be governed from a commons standpoint of local engagement, control and financing in which the critical rules are devised by locals for the benefit of locals. These are institutions, however, with limited audiences and financial needs. &#x00a0;I also could extend their model, with adjustments, to institutions that may be owned and funded by governments, but only by governments that are tolerant of innovative uses of collections and spaces to serve local community needs.&#x00a0; Nina Simon&#x2019;s vision for the &#x201c;Participatory Museum,&#x201d; based on her experience at the city-owned by autonomous museum in Santa Cruz, California, illustrates many of these principles. Hers, however, was a free-entry museum in a very &#x201c;liberal&#x201d; community.&#x00a0; Many museums in the US and abroad are experimenting with community-curated exhibits and projects, but that is not the same thing as being community-driven.&#x00a0; Indeed, the larger and more prominent the GLAM enterprise, the more that governance realities intrude on an idealized version of how a &#x201c;commons-oriented&#x201d; GLAM would work.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Second, and related,, in the case of large institutions (think the major Universal Museums, civically owned museums, libraries and so forth), the stakeholders engaged in these institutions are numerous (government owners, often separate government funders, philanthropic donors, professionalized staff members, sophisticated administrators, lenders and other financial overseers).&#x00a0; That complexity essentially makes the idealized notion of community-led, commons-oriented governance impossible.&#x00a0; Participatory measures that are taken may be token, and obstacles to community control impossible to surmount, especially where budgets are measured in millions of dollars or the equivalent. Such institutions, realistically, are unlikely to be &#x201c;re-assembled in ways that will enable increased possibilities for museum staff and communities to assert control&#x201d; (p7). Indeed, in many cases the professional staffs themselves would be opposed to delegating curation and presentation to non-&#x201c;expert&#x201d; community members.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The authors suggest solutions, such as the representation of community members on governing boards or management and that rules and norms be assembled in a self-regulated manner. While the former is possible, it hardly emulates the sorts of self-organization and self-regulation envisioned in the commons literature. The latter, I would argue is exceedingly unlikely outside of small, local contexts. Legal ownership, fiduciary responsibility of directors, labour relations, and access all militate against a radical commoning of larger-scale and complex GLAM governance. It is not enough to say these things must change, as the authors do. They need to confront the reality that these changes fly in the face of substantial political, legal, economic and attitudinal realities. Not the least of these is that larger scale GLAMs require enormous amounts of money to operate, entitling the providers of such money (governments or philanthropists) almost insurmountable leverage over the conduct of the GLAM institution.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> I also am concerned that the authors have not acknowledged the contestation within communities themselves. Often &#x201c;communities&#x201d; based on geographic proximity are highly discordant in their values, aims and interests. One consequence of an idealized view of communities is that it tends to produce an expectation that &#x201c;community generated&#x201d; content will be more inclusive of differences and expressive of tolerance. There are, in fact, no guarantees of this outcome. Communities around the world are notoriously not homogeneous, but it is commonplace in scholarly literature to act as if they are.&#x00a0; Ostrom&#x2019;s work i demonstrates the need for communities to resolve such differences and admits of the difficulty of doing so as commons institutions increase in scale.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The authors identify three &#x201c;key principles that determine GLAMs&#x2019; potential to operate as commons: (a) governance, (b) autonomy and (c) accessibility&#x201d; (p10). My essential recommendation for this paper is that the authors ponder the implications of the arguments I am presenting and either offer a more nuanced evaluation of how the realities of scale, ownership/management structures, and financial dependence require them to modify their arguments 
                <italic>and/or</italic> suggest how, in the context of real-world GLAM operations, they could feasibly adapt larger-scale GLAMs to overcome the limitations in governance, autonomy and accessibility that interfere with their vision of a commons-oriented GLAM sector.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Let me emphasize that the matter these authors are exploring is of the utmost importance, and they are clearly equipped to make substantive contributions to advancing the GLAM sector in the ways they wish.&#x00a0; Perhaps, however, they stop too soon. I would hope that they have ideas for solutions to the issues I raise. At a minimum, they need to acknowledge these complexities more clearly and pose as future research priorities the identification of viable alternatives to contemporary realities.</p>
